arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: This collection is organized in two series: Membership card catalog and Subject files.

custodhist.head: Custodial History
custodhist.p: Many of the records in this collections were originally part of the Activities and Organizations collection compiled by Russell Miller.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: This collection was originally created by Russell Miller in the process of preparing his history of Tufts University, Light on the Hill; original order of material was not maintained. As of fall 2010 the collection had been partially processed by students but never completed. In fall 2010, Lara Ullman, Simmons intern, reassessed and reprocessed parts of the collection and corrected the finding aid; supervisor Susanne Belovari, Archivist for Reference and Collections, DCA. As part of reprocessing, some duplicates were weeded. Student transcripts used to determine eligibility for PBK were left in the collection, first, because they indicate selection criteria, and second because some of these transcripts might currently be missing in the Office of Program Support records. If missing years of student transcripts in UA072 cannot be obtained, a cross-reference will point to UA025 records.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This collection document the activities of the Delta Chapter of Phi Beta Kappa (PBK) at Tufts University and consists of artifacts, the membership card catalog (up until 1978), and subject files. Significant topics in this collection include the recruitment and initiation of new Tufts University Phi Beta Kappa members.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Delta Chapter of Phi Beta Kappa (PBK), a national honorary society, was chartered on September 7, 1892, 1892 through the efforts of Thomas Wentworth Higginson, President of the United Chapters, Professor William R. Shipman, a member of the society at Middlebury College and the first librarian at Tufts, and Professor Frank Pierrepont Graves, a professor of classics while at Tufts and a member of the society at Columbia University - the year before the original chapter at the College of William and Mary was reactivated. The Tufts chapter was the fourth in the state to be established, and hence the designation "Delta." Nationally, women were first admitted to Phi Beta Kappa in 1875. Among the first cohort of women studying at Tufts, two were initiated into Phi Beta Kappa in 1896; there were a total of six initiates that year.

The PBK Executive Board of Delta Chapter at Tufts University elects students in the spring who show academic excellence in a wide array of disciplines, as well as intellectual commitment, originality and achievement in a particular area, and the quality of mind characteristic of a true scholar.

Handwritten reference card lists the following categories, however white cards were also used for male members.T he original color code was explained in an index card, filed in-front of the alphabetical run Series 1, Item 1.
White cards: Regular card. Maiden name of women used in filing order if unmarried at time of initiation. Brown/Yellow cards: Married Name of Women. Blue: Faculty. Pink: Honorary.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Each membership card contains a variable number of elements. Elements present on nearly every card in this drawer: member's name (maiden name), address, date initiated, and graduation class year. Other less common elements are: graduation date, alternate written addresses, current status (current school year), Phi Beta Kappa degree date, date elected, maiden name, and husband's name. On the back of about half of the cards are a list of dates when a member paid dues.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Predecessor of "Phi Beta Kappa Delta of Mass-Tufts Members in Course Members A-Z" [archivist created title] including less information and data elements than previous sections. It is arranged alphabetically without any additional tabs. The four main elements on each cards are: name, address, graduation class, and dues paid. There occasionally is a stamped date, which may be when the card was entered into the card catalog system, or when the member's address and details were updated.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains include correspondence, student transcripts, meetings and minutes among other material. Historical records of Phi Beta Kappa were arranged chronologically at the beginning of the series, followed by an alphabetical run of subject files; ephemera included at the end.
